Kung Fu and Titties is a cinematic masterpiece that left me yearning for more. The run time is only one and a half hours and my only complaint is that this did not leave enough time to fully develop many of the underlying issues taking place with the more complex and multilayered characters.
Be that as it may, neither Shakespeare, Nietzche,  nor Freud so adequately captured the very nature  of humanity itself as the writers of this film. The sacred titty, those fleshy jewels,  that have driven man to his highest heights and lowest lows, are showcased in all their glory.
While every man aspire to be Richard Titty,  the noble hero at war with himself, the more introspective amongst us know that at our core, we are no better, and alas no worse,  than Zeefros. We may jeer at him for his single minded obsession with finding the perfect pair of breasts,  shunning love and true intimacy, and we can even find his beastly pursuit abhorrent,  if we are to be truly honest with ourselves, the sort of honesty normally reserved for foxholes and sleepless nights, we must own up to our envy for him and accept that we are little more than a poorly evolved mammalian species.
For its ability to make us question our very nature, I give this film 5 stars.
